The three statements below describe the end of the Second World War in Europe. Analyze the five numbered sentences to determine which one BEST supports each statement. Then write the number for each sentence you select in the box beside the statement that the text describes.
THIS PROBLEM HAS THREE PARTS.
Statement: The Second World War left much of Europe in ruins.

:box:One long-term effect of the Second World War was a dramatic change in world foreign relations. :MC-A: The German surrender on May 8, 1945, gave the Allies victory in Europe but left own countries but the continent as a whole. :MC-B: Earlier that year, leaders from Great Britain, the Soviet Union, and the United States had met at Yalta to begin planning for this enormous task. They found general agreement on the question of how to administer Germany after the war, agreeing to divide the country plus its capital city of Berlin, into four zones of control. :MC-C: They also agreed that Germany should pay for some of the costs of the war. :MC-D: However, when leaders from the three countries met at Potsdam in the summer of 1945 to discuss details, they found less common ground. From this point forward, relations between East and West continued to deteriorate. :MC-E: This tension between freedom and democracy, as represented by the United States, and communism, as represented by the Soviet Union, lasted for more than four decades.

This excerpt is from a 1910 speech in which former President Theodore Roosevelt outlined his plans for a “square deal” that would benefit the American people by reducing the influence of corporations on elected officials. Select TWO sentences that BEST describe specific reforms he proposed to reduce the influence of corporations on elected officials.

:box::MC-A: Corporate expenditures for political purposes, and especially such expenditures by public-service corporations, have supplied one of the principal sources of corruption in our political affairs...

 :MC-B: ... It is particularly important that all moneys received or expended for campaign purposes should be publicly accounted for, not only after election, but before election as well. :MC-C: Political action must be made simpler, easier, and freer from confusion for every citizen. :MC-D: I believe that the prompt removal of unfaithful or incompetent public servants should be made easy and sure in whatever way experience shall show to be most expedient in any given class of cases.

 :MC-E: One of the fundamental necessities in a representative government such as ours is to make certain that the men to whom the people delegate their power shall serve the people by whom they are elected, and not the special interests. :MC-F: I believe that every national officer, elected or appointed, should be forbidden to perform any service or receive any compensation, directly or indirectly, from interstate corporations; and a similar provision could not fail to be useful within the States.
